{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16256"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16256"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.6,0.15,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8947"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8947"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1800"},{"type":"tags","id":"2286"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34530"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with progressive shortness of breath over two weeks. He denies chest pain or fever. He recalls falling down a flight of stairs six weeks ago but did not seek medical attention at the time. He has a medical history of cirrhosis due to alcohol use disorder and continues to drink heavily. He takes no regular medications. He is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history and works as a construction worker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears short of breath but comfortable at rest. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 128/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals reduced breath sounds and dullness to percussion on the left side, but no tenderness to palpation. Abdominal examination reveals hepatomegaly and mild ascites. A chest X-ray shows a large left-sided pleural effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diagnostic thoracentesis is performed (Image). Laboratory analysis of the pleural fluid shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.45\u003Cbr /\u003ETriglycerides: 3.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;1.24)\u003Cbr /\u003EProtein: 45 g/L\u003Cbr /\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 320 U/L \u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 2.5 x 10^9/L with lymphocyte predominance\u003Cbr /\u003EMicroscopy: No organisms seen\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum reference ranges\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.35 - 7.45\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein: 60-80g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate Dehydrogenase: \u0026lt;250 U/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatic hydrothorax","Chylothorax","Empyema","Parapneumonic effusion","Malignant pleural effusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with chylothorax following blunt chest trauma. The delayed presentation is typical as lymphatic fluid accumulates gradually over days to weeks. Unlike other pleural effusions, chylothorax tends to be painless because chyle is not irritating to the pleural surface. While there is a mild fever, significant pyrexia is uncommon in chylothorax. The key diagnostic features are the milky white appearance of the pleural fluid and elevated triglyceride levels above 1.24 mmol/L, which are pathognomonic for chylothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChylothorax\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is accumulation of lymphatic fluid (chyle) in the pleural space, usually due to disruption of the thoracic duct. Trauma is a common cause, although in this case, given the patient\u0027s age, smoking history, and alcohol use, malignancy must also be considered. The fluid is characteristically milky white and rich in triglycerides and lymphocytes. Chylothorax is typically an exudative effusion due to the high protein content of lymphatic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic hydrothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in patients with cirrhosis due to the passage of ascitic fluid through diaphragmatic defects. However, the fluid would be transudative with low protein and LDH levels, unlike the exudative picture seen here. The elevated triglycerides and milky appearance are not features of hepatic hydrothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpyema\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by purulent pleural fluid with high neutrophil count and often low glucose and pH levels. It typically presents with fever, chest pain, and systemic symptoms. The fluid would appear cloudy or frankly purulent, not milky white, and would typically show neutrophil predominance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParapneumonic effusion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in association with pneumonia and would typically show neutrophil predominance and may have low pH and glucose levels. Patients usually present with fever, chest pain, and symptoms of pneumonia. The lymphocyte predominance and milky appearance are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E can have variable appearances and should be considered in this patient given his age and smoking history. However, the characteristic milky appearance and elevated triglycerides make chylothorax the more likely immediate diagnosis. Further investigation for underlying malignancy would be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of traumatic chylothorax typically involves chest tube drainage, dietary modification (low fat or medium-chain triglycerides), and possible surgical intervention if conservative measures fail. In this case, given the patient\u0027s risk factors, further investigation for underlying malignancy would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESee below for an image of a chylothorax drain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chylothorax should be suspected when pleural fluid appears milky white, even if presentation is delayed after trauma.","The presence of chylomicrons and triglycerides \u003E1.24 mmol/L in pleural fluid confirms chylothorax.","Chylothorax is typically painless and afebrile as chyle does not irritate the pleura.","Chylothorax is typically an exudative effusion due to high protein content of lymphatic fluid."],"references":["Riley LE, Ataya A. Clinical approach and review of causes of a chylothorax. Respiratory medicine. 2019 Oct 1;157:7-13.","Pillay TG, Singh B. A review of traumatic chylothorax. Injury. 2016 Mar 1;47(3):545-50."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16256"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21730"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21322"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21730"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/XGb